<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305075894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0753 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 3 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu reiterated Tuesday that replacing the 
Korean Armistice Agreement with a peace pact is a matter for 
Seoul and Pyongyang, not Pyongyang and Washington, to work out. 
  "The United States is a signatory of the Armistice and 
therefore will get involved in that sense," Han told reporters, 
"but Washington fully agrees with Seoul that the matter is for 
the two Koreas to resolve." 
  North Korea will end up hindering high-level dialogue with 
the United States if it insists on the change, Han said. "The 
next round of North Korea-U.S. dialogue will not discuss this 
issue." 
  Pyongyang unilaterally announced last week that it was 
withdrawing from the Military Armistice Commission but would 
keep on its commission secretaries and liaison officers. 
  In addition, it announced that Poland, a Neutral Nations 
Supervisory Commission (NNSC) member chosen by North Korea, will 
be withdrawn from the commission. 
  Han said the North was trying to isolate the South in 
talking 
only with the United States and trying to "break up" Seoul- 
Washington relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

