<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Command in Korea Cited on DPRK Move </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Command in Korea Cited on DPRK Move </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0205125094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1107 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0205125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 2 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has expressed 
the intent of withdrawing from the Military Armistice 
Commission, officials at the United Nations Command [UNC] in 
Korea said on Monday. 
  In addition, North Korea has let it be known that they would 
remove Polish members from the Neutral Nations Supervisory 
Commission, a UNC official at the Armistice Commission said. 
Early last year, North Korea withdrew Czech delegates from the 
truce-watching commission. Poland and Czechoslovakia had been 
the communist-side-chosen member countries of the four-country 
supervisory commission, whose delegates were responsible for 
watching the North Korean area. 
  The planned withdrawal by North Korea is an express 
violation 
of the Armistice Agreement, over the issue of which the U.N. 
Command has been contacting North Korean delegates and UNC 
member countries related to the maintenance of the truce 
agreement, a UNC official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

