<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Policy for Repatriation of DPRK Loggers Reaffirmed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Policy for Repatriation of DPRK Loggers Reaffirmed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2904021694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0159 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2904021694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 29 (YONHAP) -- Song Yong-tae, vice 
minister of the National Unification Board, reaffirmed Friday 
that the government will go ahead with its policy of seeking 
early repatriation of North Korean loggers in Russia. 
  Speaking to business leaders at a breakfast meeting held 
under the auspices of the Korea Management Association at the 
Hyatt Hotel, Song also said various government agencies were 
devising measures to help the loggers settle in South Korea. 
  While delivering a speech entitled "The Outlook for the 
North 
Korean Nuclear Problem and the Seoul-Pyongyang Relationship," 
Song revealed that Pyongyang has stopped issuing travel 
certificates to North Koreans and strictly limited entry by 
foreigners since mid-March in an apparent effort to heighten 
internal tension. 
  Pyongyang recently increased military activity 50 percent 
and 
resumed anti-air raid drills in the Yongbyon area, which Western 
countries suspect has facilities capable of producing nuclear 
weapons, Song said. North Korea had suspended the drills in the 
Yongbyon area last June. 

</TEXT>

