<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government `Regret' at Placement on Watch List </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government `Regret' at Placement on Watch List </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305055294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0517 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305055294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 3 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean Government 
expressed regret Tuesday at Washington's placing of Seoul on the 
priority watch list for intellectual property protection 
violations. 
  "We regret that the United States one-sidedly evaluated the 
intellectual property protection situation of its trade partner 
according to its domestic laws, despite international efforts to 
resolve all disputes at the multilateral level before the 
launching of the World Trade Organization (WTO)," Foreign 
Ministry Spokesman Chang Ki-ho said in a statement. 
  The U.S. Trade Representative placed South Korea on the 
priority watch list on Monday, claiming that Seoul had failed to 
improve its laws on protection of intellectual property rights 
[IPR]. 
  "We want to clarify our government position that we will 
continue to implement the agreements, both bilateral and 
multilateral, on IPR protection," the statement said. 

</TEXT>

