<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   To Suspend Status on Other Goods </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    To Suspend Status on Other Goods </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305081294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0543 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305081294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 3 (YONHAP) -- The European Union is 
poised to stop granting Generalized System of Preference (GSP) 
status to such South Korean products as consumer electronics, 
cars, semiconductors and footwear, indicating the union no 
longer sees Korea as a developing country. 
  According to a report released by the Korea Trade Promotion 
Corp. (KOTRA) Tuesday, the European Association of Consumer 
Electronics Manufacturers (EACEM) has demanded that the EU 
commission withdraw the GSP status of South Korea, Singapore, 
Taiwan and Hong Kong. The group insists that GSP treatment, 
intended to promote economic progress in developing countries, 
actually benefits only a few advanced developing nations. 
  In a report titled "The effect of GSP on the European 
consumer electronics and lightning apparatus industries," the 
EACEM argued that GSP treatment only enables the advanced 
developing countries to further penetrate the European market, 
KOTRA said. 
  In compliance with the demands of the EACEM and other 
industry members, the EU commission is likely to withdraw 
special treatment for consumer electronics from South Korea and 
other advanced developing countries beginning July 1 when the 
commission announces its GSP policy for 1994, according to the 
KOTRA report. 
  Meanwhile, the European Association of Automobile 
Manufacturers (ACEA), the European Electronic Component 
Manufacturers' Association (EECA) and the European footwear 
industry have joined forces with the EACEM in demanding the 
suspension of GSP status for goods from South Korea and other 
advanced East Asian Countries -- in the form of complaints filed 
with the EU commission over the past months. 
  KOTRA sources believe the EU's move foreshadows a formal 
decision to suspend special treatment for cars, semiconductors 
and footwear from East Asian countries. 
  Officials from KOTRA expect that the new EU policy on GSP 
effective July 1 will include suspension of GSP status for such 
key South Korean exports as textile products, autos, 
semiconductors and footwear. 
  They noted that the associations of various industries, 
which 
asked the EU commission to drop GSP treatment for products from 
advanced developing countries including South Korea, represent 
each industry and are influential enough in Europe to sway 
public opinion. 
  Moreover, Europeans no longer consider South Korea to be a 
developing country, they added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

