<H3> <TI>   Government Welcomes Free Election in RSA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Welcomes Free Election in RSA </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305003194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0016 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305003194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 3 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean Government 
welcomed the conclusion of free elections in South Africa [RSA] 
Tuesday and looked forward to stronger bilateral relations after 
the end of apartheid. 
  South Korea "commends the firm determination and efforts of 
South African leaders, both black and white, who have wisely 
overcome the long disharmony between the races and have made 
this election a reality," said Foreign Ministry spokesman Chang 
Ki-ho. 
  "Furthermore, the Government of the Republic of Korea is of 
the view that the present elections provide historic momentum 
for bringing about an end to the 342-year legacy of minority 
white rule over the majority black population, and the regime of 
apartheid," he said. 
  South Korea "looks forward to further strengthening the 
already existing friendly relations between our two countries 
through the momentum created by the free elections in South 
Africa," Chang said. 
  Seoul and Pretoria established diplomatic ties in December 
1992. 

</TEXT>

