<H3> <TI>   Government, Saudi Arabia To Sign Economic Pacts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government, Saudi Arabia To Sign Economic Pacts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2904005394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0038 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2904005394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 29 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and Saudi 
Arabia agreed to conclude pacts on investment guarantees and 
avoidance of double taxation at a joint committee session this 
week in Seoul, the Foreign Ministry said Friday. The two 
countries also promised to cooperate in improving conditions for 
South Korean construction companies operating in Saudi Arabia, 
the Ministry said. The committee, the 10th of its kind, was 
convened after a five-year hiatus. 
  Seoul officials captured Riyadh's interest with proposals to 
jointly bid for construction contracts in third countries and 
for South Korea to participate in the Saudis' railroad-building 
project. Saudi Arabia, in return, asked for more private-level 
economic cooperation suited to the changing political situation 
in the Middle East after the Gulf War, the drop in international 
oil prices and the conclusion of the Uruguay Round. 
  South Korea registered 3.73 billion U.S. dollars in imports 
from Saudi Arabia last year, mostly crude oil, and posted 
exports of 940 million dollars. Although a heavy imbalance may 
be inevitable due to oil purchases, officials said they want to 
rectify it as much as possible -- through a more active advance 
into the Saudi construction market, for example. Officials said 
the two sides agreed to work on expanding bilateral 
import-export activities. 

</TEXT>

