<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nation's First Submarine Delivered to Navy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nation's First Submarine Delivered to Navy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK3004102194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0829 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3004102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 30 (YONHAP) -- Daewoo Shipbuilding and 
Heavy Machinery, Ltd. delivered the nation's first submarine 
"Ichon" to the Navy in a ceremony held at the company's Okpo 
Shipyard near Pusan over the weekend, with chief of naval 
operations Adm. Kim Hong-yol, Daewoo Vice Chairman Yun Yong-sok 
and many other Navy and company officials attending, the company 
announced. 
  The diesel engine-powered T-209-class submarine is armed 
with 
torpedoes and depth charges and can conduct independent 
operations for two months with a crew of 30. 
  It can cruise at a maximum speed of 22 knots (40 kilometers 
per hour), compared with North Korea's Whiskey- and Romeo-class 
submarines cruising at 12 to 14 knots, the announcement said. 
  Daewoo started construction of the warship in November 1989, 
using designs and technology of Germany's HDW, and completed it 
in October 1992. The ship had been successfully test-operated 
before the delivery to the Navy. 

</TEXT>

