<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Announces `Streamlining' Finalized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Announces `Streamlining' Finalized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0205094194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0830 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0205094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 2 (YONHAP) -- Twenty-two, or 60 percent, 
of the 38 central government agencies have undergone 
streamlining to honor the pledge of a "small government" made in 
January. At a meeting Monday presided over by Prime Minister Yi 
Yong-tok, the cabinet confirmed that 1,368 officials have been 
cut while 829 have been newly employed, resulting in a net 
reduction of 539 officials. One office, three bureaus, 11 
councilor posts and 35 divisions have been closed down. Of the 
remaining 16 agencies, four agencies are awaiting approval for a 
manpower increase while 12 others, including the National 
Unification Board, have yet to submit reorganization drafts. 
  The government streamlining is therefore virtually finalized 
as the rest of the reshaping is likely to be small in scale. Of 
the 22 agencies that have finished their restructuring, the 
Communications Ministry did the most cutting -- 223 officials -- 
followed by 115 in the Korea National Railroad, 105 in the 
Construction Ministry, 55 in the Home Ministry, 52 in the 
Foreign Ministry, 43 in the Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry, 
and 23 in the Government Administration Ministry. 
  In contrast, the Environment Ministry added 223 officials to 
perform its new task of handling water-related affairs and the 
public prosecutor's office employed seven. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

