<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank of Korea Governor Estimates Economic Growth </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bank of Korea Governor Estimates Economic Growth </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK3004124794 Seoul YONHAP in English 1226 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3004124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 30 (YONHAP) -- Bank of Korea Governor 
Kim Myong-ho estimated Saturday the first-quarter growth of the 
economy at above 8.5 percent. Kim said in a press conference 
before his departure for Manila to attend the annual Asian 
Development Bank meeting that the economic growth in the 
January-March period was estimated to be more than 8.5 percent, 
thanks to increased exports and capital investment in all 
sectors except agriculture, though the estimate was not based on 
accurate data. 
  Kim's estimate is compared with the 8.3-percent growth 
estimated by the Korea Development Institute, indicating that 
the economy will grow 8 percent this year against the Bank of 
Korea's earlier projection of 6.3 percent. 
  It is too early to say that the economy is overheating 
because the economy is not yet showing such signs of overheating 
as supply shortages and rapid wage hikes. But the economy has 
entered an expansion period after a recovery from the recession, 
he observed. 
  Commenting on the current-account deficit of 2.5 billion 
U.S. 
dollars recorded in the first quarter, he said, "When the 
economy is recovering or expanding, imports are usually greater 
than exports chiefly because of the rapidly increasing demand 
for imported equipment and machinery. So, the deficit is a 
temporary phenomenon and I think it will not last long until the 
end of the year." 
  Kim said there would be no revision of the money supply 
growth goal of 14-17 percent for this year because the financial 
situation is so good that such revision is not needed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51809 </DOCNO>
