<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Reports Speedy Settlement of Wage Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Reports Speedy Settlement of Wage Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2704113994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1113 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2704113994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 27 (YONHAP) -- Wage negotiations have 
been settled at South Korean industries at a rapider pace so far 
this year than last year. 
  According to the Labor Affairs Ministry, 812 firms or 14.8 
percent of the total 5,483 companies employing more than 100 
workers have concluded labor-management wage negotiations as of 
Tuesday. The percentage represented an increase of 3.2 
percentage points over the same period of last year. 
  A Ministry official said the faster settlement was 
attributable to the fact that a central labor-management wage 
agreement came earlier than last year, and many industries had 
affirmatively accepted the wage agreement. The wage hikes 
agreed on thus far averaged at 5.3 percent, which compares with 
the average 5.2 percent of last year. By area, service firms 
topped the list with 24.1 percent followed by electricity, gas 
and water works (22.7 percent), transportation, warehouse and 
communications (20.5 percent), manufacturing (12.1 percent), 
construction (10.9 percent) and financing and insurance (5.1 
percent). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

