<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hanjin Heavy Industry Union Secedes From FKTU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hanjin Heavy Industry Union Secedes From FKTU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2804133994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1101 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2804133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pusan, April 28 (YONHAP) -- The labor union of the 
Hanjin Heavy Industry Co. on Thursday seceded from the 
Federation of Korean Trade Unions (FKTU) in protest against the 
recommended wage increase of 5 percent for this year earlier 
agreed on between the FKTU and the Korea Employers Federation. 
It is the third major trade union to leave the FKTU. The two 
others are the Association of Hyundai Group Unions and the 
Council of Daewoo Group Unions. 
  The Hanjin union decided on the secession in a vote 
participated by 46 union delegates. Of them, 41 voted for the 
withdrawal and two against. Three others abstained. 
  "The wage increase recommended by the FKTU and Employers 
Federation is something that undermines the development of trade 
unions. The cessation reflects the anger of all our unionists 
at the recommended wage hike," a union official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51812 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas085_d_94055" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Overseas Investment Rises 250% in First Quarter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Overseas Investment Rises 250% in First Quarter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2404060594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0540 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2404060594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 24 (YONHAP) -- South Korea's corporate 
investment in foreign countries in the first quarter amounted to 
466 million U.S. dollars, up 250 percent from a year earlier, 
according to the Finance Ministry. The sharp increase was 
attributed to greatly relaxed rules governing foreign 
investment. The manufacturing sector accounted for 70 percent 
of the amount, and trade, transportation, construction and 
fisheries the rest. 
  North America was the top investment market for South Korean 
industries, representing 46 percent, or 214 million dollars, 
thanks to brisk investment in computer parts factories in the 
area. Asia placed second with 32 percent and Europe third with 
19 percent. Investment by small- and medium-sized businesses 
also increased 55 percent from the same quarter of last year, 
indicating that small-amount overseas investment was steadily 
increasing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

