<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   16 Firms Vie for High-Speed Train Phone Contract </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    16 Firms Vie for High-Speed Train Phone Contract </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2504073794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0636 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2504073794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 25 (YONHAP) -- The Korea High-Speed 
Rail Construction Authority (KHRC) announced Monday the list of 
consortiums, comprised of eight local and eight foreign 
companies, seeking the cellular system contract for the 
Seoul-Pusan high-speed railway slated to open in 2002. The 
Seoul-Pusan high-speed line will be the world's first to adopt a 
time-division multiple access (TDMA) cellular system, widely 
used by U.S. telecom companies in their cellular phone networks, 
a KHRC spokesman said. 
  Existing bullet trains -- the TGV (Train a Grande Vitesse) 
of 
France, the ICE (Inter-City Express) of Germany and Sinkansen of 
Japan -- all use the less sensitive analog technology. 
  The applicants are ASCOM of Switzerland (with participation 
by Korea's Goldstar Information and Communications), Motorola of 
the United States (together with Hantong Engineering), Siemens 
of Germany (Siemens Korea), Ericsson GE of the United States 
(Samsung Electronics and Kukje Electronics), AMCE and Union 
Pacific of the United States (Ujin Electronics), AEG of Germany 
(Hyundai Electronics) and Rohill of the Netherlands (Tongyang 
Telecommuncations). 
  The KHRC will choose five successful companies by April 29 
and send them RFP (Request For Proposal) so that it can name the 
final awardees by year-end after screening their proposals from 
June. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

