<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Produces Witness List in Scandal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Produces Witness List in Scandal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2304105794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0821 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2304105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 23 (YONHAP) -- The opposition 
Democratic Party [DP] on Saturday made public a list of 51 
persons it chose as witnesses and references to be used in the 
planned parliamentary probe into the Sangmudae scandal. The 
ruling and opposition parties have agreed to have an assembly 
inspection of the suspected diversion of part of Sangmudae 
construction funds into political funds in late 1992. 
  Acting DP Head Kim Won-ki said his party had decided to 
include in the list all those suspected of having played parts 
in the scandal. 
  Among the 29 listed references were President Kim Yong-sam, 
former President No Tae-u and ex-rep. So Sok-chae. The 
witnesses selected numbered 22, who included the Rev. So Eui- 
hyon, disgraced ex-head of the Buddhist Chogye order 
secretariat; Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae; Justice Minister Kim 
Tu-hi; ex- Defense Minister Yi Chong-ku; DLP [Democratic 
Liberal Party] Rep. Kim Yun-hwan; and former Chongwadae 
[presidential office] Protective Service Head Yi Hyon-u. 
  It is not likely that all of them will actually be used as 
witnesses or references in the upcoming probe as the ruling 
party is determined to use only those whose role in the alleged 
fund diversion can be substantiated by actual evidences. 

</TEXT>

