<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owada on Desire for Permanent UNSC Seat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Owada on Desire for Permanent UNSC Seat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305040994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0329 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305040994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New York, May 2 KYODO -- Hisashi Owada, Japanese 
ambassador to the United Nations, declared Monday [2 May] that 
Japan will make clear its resolve to get permanent membership on 
the U.N. Security Council [UNSC]. "It is very important to make 
clear Japan's determination," Owada told Japanese reporters four 
days after presenting his credentials to U.N. Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali. 
  He said Japan would try to achieve the objective without 
antagonizing other countries. "The sentiment in the U.N. and 
the world community is that Japan should play a more active 
role," he said. 
  Owada also said it is "very important" for the U.N. to 
engage 
in peacekeeping and other related activities, adding there is 
still room for Japan to do more within its peacekeeping 
cooperation law. 
  Owada, father of Crown Princess Masako, took up his U.N. 
post 
on April 28, replacing another career diplomat Yoshio Hatano. 

</TEXT>

