<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fukuoka Welcomes Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fukuoka Welcomes Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405113694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1055 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0405113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Fukuoka, May 4 KYODO -- The city of Fukuoka on 
Wednesday [4 May] welcomed a proposal to host the annual meeting 
of the Asian Development Bank [ADB] in 1997. "I'm convinced 
that our city is eligible because the Asian Development Bank's 
policy of contributing to development in the Asia-Pacific region 
matches Fukuoka city's policy," Fukuoka Mayor Keiichi Kuwahara 
said. 
  Kuwahara made the statement after Japanese Finance Minister 
Hirohisa Fujii proposed the holding of the 30th annual meeting 
of the ADB in 1997 in Fukuoka at an ADB annual meeting in Nice, 
France Wednesday. Fukuoka is located in the northern part of 
Kyushu, the most southwestern main island of Japan. 
  "It's a great pleasure. It will help make not only Fukuoka 
but also Kyushu better known" said Tatsuo Kawai, chairman of the 
Kyushu-Yamaguchi Economic Federation, a local business group. 
  The Fukuoka business community hopes that by holding the ADB 
meeting in their city, it will enhance its image as a city open 
to Asia. 

</TEXT>

