<H3> <TI>   Ouchi Opposes Multiseat Constituencies Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ouchi Opposes Multiseat Constituencies Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305061394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0433 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, May 2 KYODO -- Health and Welfare Minister 
Keigo Ouchi, who is chairman of the Democratic Socialist Party 
(DSP), said Monday [2 May] he is against the idea of holding 
general elections under the existing system of multi-seat 
constituencies. He said the government of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata has been born amid the electoral system reform 
movement and that he does not see any need to hold the next 
general elections under "the old system" which will be replaced 
by a new electoral system for the House of Representatives. 
  Ouchi made the remarks at a news conference after arriving 
in 
Geneva to attend a general meeting of the World Health 
Organization. 
  The new electoral system features a combination of 300 
single-seat constituencies and 200 proportional representation 
seats and reduces the total number of lower house seats from the 
current 511. 
  Asked to comment on Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] 
Secretary 
General Ichiro Ozawa, a backroom strategist of the coalition 
government, Ouchi said Ozawa is "high-handed" when it comes to 
the democratic process. "(His) initiatives for welfare tax and 
a cabinet reshuffle were not at times appropriate," Ouchi said, 
referring to the botched schemes which widened the division 
within the coalition government of former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

