<H3> <TI>   New Party Mirai Urges New Electoral System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Party Mirai Urges New Electoral System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305102294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0903 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305102294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 3 KYODO -- The leader of New Party Mirai 
(Future), a five-member group in the House of Representatives, 
said Wednesday [as received] the next general election must be 
conducted under a new electoral system that combines 300 single 
seats and 200 others chosen through proportional representation. 
  In issuing a party statement, Michihiko Kano said the Diet 
must enact a bill to delineate constituencies during the current 
150-day regular session, which may be extended past the June 29 
deadline in order to pass it. 
  New Party Mirai's statement countered calls from both the 
ruling and opposition parties for an early dissolution of the 
House of Representatives for a snap general election even under 
the existing multiseat constituencies. 
  Kano and four others quit the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) 
last month amid political unrest sparked by then Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa's April 8 announcement to resign. They formed 
the new party on April 18. 

</TEXT>

