<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ, JCP: Hata Trying To Spoil Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ, JCP: Hata Trying To Spoil Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0205130694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1117 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0205130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 2 KYODO -- Two left-wing opposition 
parties said Monday [2 May] the new cabinet of Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata is trying to spoil the war-renouncing Constitution. 
  The Social Democratic Party [of Japan, SDPJ] (SDP) and the 
Japanese Communist Party (JCP) issued separate statements on the 
eve of the 47th anniversary of the Constitution. 
  The SDP, which quit the coalition last week to turn [as 
received] the No. 2 opposition party, said it wants to protest 
against what it called the "dangerous intentions" of the 
administration. 
  "We are worried that some members of the Hata administration 
are supporting collective defense, forbidden under the 
Constitution, and supposing `emergencies' on the Korean 
peninsula, and that they have spoken with the intention of 
changing the Constitution in order to deal with the situation," 
the SDP said. 
  The JCP said, "the new administration is trying to impose an 
extraordinary system and an emergency system on the people, on 
the pretext of `sanctions' against North Korea." 
  "We take it seriously that some ministers have urged the 
government to change its current interpretation that resorting 
to collective defense is a violation of the Constitution," the 
JCP said. 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa and Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Hiroshi Kumagai have expressed support for legislation to deal 
with emergencies including possible international sanctions 
against North Korea related to Pyongyang's suspected nuclear 
weapons development. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51832 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas086_a_94012" </HT>


