<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rice Transactions by Zenno Drop to 13-Year Low </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rice Transactions by Zenno Drop to 13-Year Low </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405063394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0546 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0405063394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 4 KYODO -- Rice transactions by 
agricultural cooperatives across the nation in the rice year 
ended last June dropped to a 13-year low due to the worst 
harvest in the postwar period, the National Federation of 
Agricultural Cooperative Associations (Zenno) reported Wednesday 
[4 May]. 
  The federation said the value of its rice trading stood at 
1.69 trillion yen, down 441.5 billion yen from the preceding 
year. It was the first time in 13 years that rice trading fell 
below 2 trillion yen, it said. 
  Zenno handles 95 percent of the nation's rice harvest 
annually. The federation earlier estimated the value of its rice 
trading in the 1993 rice year at 2,284.6 billion yen, up 153.1 
billion yen over the year before. The previous low of 1.9 
trillion yen was recorded in the 1980 rice year. The federation 
forecast rice trading will recover the 2 trillion yen level in 
the current year and total 2,220.6 billion yen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

