<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-086 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banks Create Plan To Avert Credit Crises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Banks Create Plan To Avert Credit Crises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305015294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0118 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305015294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 3 KYODO -- Japan's 11 major commercial 
banks have agreed to cooperate to avert credit crises caused by 
their own liquidity shortages, the NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN said 
Tuesday [3 May]. 
  At the behest of the Bank of Japan (BOJ), the 11 banks have 
created a scheme under which, when one of them lapses into a 
liquidity crisis through failure to secure necessary amounts of 
cash in the money market, the others are required to make 
low-interest, emergency loans to the beleagured bank. The plan 
calls for up to 300 billion yen in loans per bank, which means 
the maximum available funds for the troubled bank could run as 
much as 3 trillion yen. 
  In practice, the loans would be made in the form of the 
rescuers' purchase of certificates of deposit (CDs) issued by 
the institution in crisis. 
  The bigger of the 11 "city banks" each procure 2-3 trillion 
yen of funds daily in interbank trading on the Tokyo money 
market. 
  Currently, the BOJ is required to come to rescue of 
institutions which are unable to secure the necessary sums. But 
concerned that fund shortages could exceed its capacity, the BOJ 
has strongly called on the 11 institutions to establish their 
own support system to handle cases of credit crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51836 </DOCNO>
