<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transfers Suggested To Ease Employment Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Transfers Suggested To Ease Employment Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0205125794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0829 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0205125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 2 KYODO -- Japanese companies have 
reached the point where they can no longer sustain employment 
simply by replacing workers within their own business groups and 
must consider sending them to other firms, including ones 
overseas, a governmental panel said in a report Monday [2 May]. 
  The report, on the issue of boosting employment, 
particularly 
for middle-aged white collar workers, was compiled by the 
advisory panel to the Labor Ministry's Employment Security 
Bureau chief. 
  It said middle-aged workers should accept being transferred 
outside of their company group in order to remain in employment, 
and that such transfers should be allowed to be permanent if 
those workers agree. 
  Also, companies should consider sending "excess" workers 
overseas to Southeast Asia or Eastern Europe where Japanese 
business know-how is welcomed, the report said. 
  According to a recent survey by the Management and 
Coordination Agency, the population of white collar workers aged 
over 45 swelled to 12.18 million in 1993, 18.8 percent of the 
entire workforce, from 6.07 million or 11.5 percent in 1973. 
  The increase is partly because there are now more older 
people than younger ones in Japan. 
  Many Japanese companies making streamlining efforts to cope 
with the current recession have "excess" workforce, particularly 
among their middle-aged, white collar workers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

