<H3> <TI>   Consumer Sentiment Picks Up in Jan-Mar Period </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Consumer Sentiment Picks Up in Jan-Mar Period </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504104094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1029 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- Japanese consumer 
sentiment picked up in the January-March quarter following two 
previous consecutive quarterly drops, with improving confidence 
in the labor situation, the government said Monday [25 April]. 
  The consumer sentiment index for the first quarter stood at 
a 
seasonally adjusted 38.1, up 5.6 percent from the 
October-December quarter, said the Economic Planning Agency. 
The index is a gauge of consumer expectations as to whether or 
not things will improve in six months' time in five areas 
including labor, income and prices. 
  An agency official said the recovery in consumer sentiment 
was mainly because the number of people with pessimistic 
outlooks was declining, rather than those with optimistic 
projections increasing. 

</TEXT>

