<H3> <TI>   Religionists Urge South To Support Korean Unity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Religionists Urge South To Support Korean Unity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305051394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0427 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305051394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Appeal to S. Korean Religionists" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, May 3 (KCNA) -- The spokesman of the 
Korean Religionists' Council issued a statement Monday calling 
on all religionists of South Korea to rise up in a struggle for 
the convocation of a national conference. 
  The statement says the Kim Yong-sam group of South Korea 
shows a negative attitude toward the North-proposed convocation 
of a national conference and it is resorting to criminal moves 
to unleash a nuclear war despite the unanimous protest and 
denunciation from people at home and abroad. 
  This is a heinous treachery to reduce South Korea to a 
market 
for U.S. weapons and victimise the nation for big powers, the 
statement notes, and continues: 
  Achievement of the great unity of the whole nation is the 
only way for our nation to overcome the grave difficulties 
caused by the U.S. imperialists and the Kim Yong-sam puppet 
group and realise peace and peaceful reunification of the 
country. 
  The religionists and religious organisations in the North, 
South and overseas should show their will for great national 
unity by a practical action by taking an active part in the 
patriotic struggle for the convocation of a national conference. 
  We earnestly call on all religionists of South Korea to turn 
out as one in the struggle to check and frustrate the South 
Korean authorities' confrontational moves for war and realise 
the national conference, irrespective of denomination and order. 
  The statement expresses the hope that all religious 
organisations, clergymen and laymen the world over will extend 
unstinting support and encouragement to the Korean nation in the 
efforts to build a unified country of justice and peace with 
love and reconciliation. 

</TEXT>

