<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reports on Kim Il-song Birthday Activities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More Reports on Kim Il-song Birthday Activities </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Greetings Received From Abroad </H4>

<F P=102> SK0305062894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0421 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305062894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 3 (KCNA) -- Comrade Kim Il-song, 
general secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party 
of Korea and president of the Democratic People's Republic of 
Korea, received on his birthday a message of greetings from 
Obiang Nguema Mbasogo, president and head of state of the 
Republic of Equatorial Guinea and founder-chairman of the 
Democratic Party of Equatorial Guinea. 
  Messages of greetings to him also came from A. Moroz, 
chairman of the Political Council of the Ukrainian Socialist 
Party; Madhav Kumar Nepal, general secretary of the Central 
Committee of the Nepal Communist Party (United 
Marxism-Leninism); Rashed Khan Menon, general secretary of the 
Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Bangladesh; Chairman 
Argelia Raya and International Secretary Jorge Valero of the 
Movement to Socialism of Venezuela; Chairman Rakutuvau 
Andriantiana and General Secretary Gisele Rabesahala of the 
Party of the Congress for the Independence of Madagascar; Otete 
Gaston Mboyo, national chairman of The National Movement of the 
Genuine Lumumbist Combatants of Zaire; Emile Kibala Bey a Nsien, 
national chairman of the Workers' Party of Zaire; Robert Corbin, 
general secretary of the People's National Congress of Guyana; 
Kamba Raymond, general secretary of the Congolese Communist 
Party; and Leon Nzokene, general secretary of the Congolese 
Socialist Party. 
  The messages extend warmest congratulations to President Kim 
Il- song and wish him good health and a long life. 
  The messages express full support and solidarity for the 
struggle of the Korean people for socialist construction and 
national reunification by means of confederacy. 

</TEXT>

