<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pipeline's Role in Steel Mill Production Lauded </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pipeline's Role in Steel Mill Production Lauded </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0405054594 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0501 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0405054594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 4 (KCNA) -- The long-distance 
pipeline for the transport of headings is greatly contributing 
to keeping iron and steel production on a high level at the Kim 
Chaek Iron and Steel Complex. 
  The pipeline, with an annual transport capacity of 2 million 
tons, has carried tens of millions of tons of headings after its 
commissioning. 
  Laid in 1975, it stretches 98 kilometres from the Musan iron 
ore mine, North Hamgyong Province, in the northernmost region of 
Korea, to the Kim Chaek Iron and Steel Complex, a metallurgical 
giant in Chongjin. 
  By carrying a large portion of iron headings to the complex, 
the pipeline lessens the burden of rails and motors. 
  Technicians and workers have laid double lines in the 
steepest 8 km-long section across the Kumpae ridge and improved 
the equipment for a higher rate of operation. 
  The great leader President Kim Il-song initiated the laying 
of this pipeline to fully solve the problem of iron heading 
transport in keeping with the increasing production capacity at 
the Musan mining complex and the Kim Chaek Iron and Steel 
Complex, and wisely led the work. 
  The dear leader Comrade Kim Chong-il took all necessary 
measures such as the supply of equipment and building machines 
so that the construction of the long-distance pipeline for the 
transport of headings could be finished in a short time. 
  And he sent many latest equipment and facilities after the 
construction of the transport pipeline so that it could fully 
display its potential. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

