<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Outsiders Urged Not To Intefere in Cambodia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Outsiders Urged Not To Intefere in Cambodia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0405051094 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 4 May 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> BK0405051094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri yesterday urged 
Cambodians to discuss their problems and called on outsiders to 
refrain from interfering. 
  "As long as there is no reconciliation among Cambodians, 
fighting will continue," Squadron Leader Prasong said. 
  "Other countries should not encourage division among them 
(Cambodians) or extend military support for them to fight each 
other," he added. 
  The minister reaffirmed support for a Round Table among the 
Cambodians but stressed that Thailand would not be involved in 
the peace talks. 
  "The Round Table has nothing to do with Thailand," he said. 
"The whole affair is a matter for the Cambodians in which we do 
not want to be involved," he added. 
  Thailand would extend economic, social or health assistance 
to Cambodia but will not intervene in the country's political 
affairs, he said. 
  As for fighting spilling over the border into Thailand, the 
minister said military authorities had been able to compile 
damage estimates so that the Foreign Ministry can file a report 
to the Cambodian government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

