<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former U.S. Air Base Designated as Airport </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former U.S. Air Base Designated as Airport </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0405041394 Manila THE MANILA CHRONICLE in English 29 Apr 
94 p 10 </F>

<F P=103> BK0405041394 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila THE MANILA CHRONICLE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Clark -- President Ramos yesterday issued a 
directive designation the former American military base in 
Pampanga as the future site of the country's premier 
international airport. [sentence as published] 
  But the actual development of Clark Air Base, the former 
headquarters of the U.S. 13th Air Force, into a commercial 
aviation complex will have to wait until 1998 when the effects 
of Mount Pinatubo have completely been swept away. 
  The president said the executive order creating a special 
economic zone in Clark came after he approved a masterplan 
prepared by a Japanese group for the development of a civilian 
commercial aviation complex in the former American military base. 
  Apart form an airport, the aviation complex will have space 
for aircraft maintenance and service facilities, an aircraft 
assembly and parts manufacturing plant, and other 
aviation-related industries. 
  To make the airport accessible, the president also revealed 
plans for a construction of expressways linking Clark and Subic 
as well as Clark and Metro Manila. 
  The Philippine National Railways (PNR) is also 
rehabilitating 
its tracks to access Clark which will become the nucleus of a 
rail network linking Metro Manila with the northern Luzon areas 
particularly the planned Northern Luzon Quadrangle which is 
composed of Pangasinan, La Union, the two Ilocos provinces and 
Baguio City in Benguet. 
  The president said the development of Clark as a aviation 
complex will help ease congestion at the Ninoy Aquino 
International Airport (NAIA) in Metro Manila. 

</TEXT>

