<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials in US Meat Issue Face Punishment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials in US Meat Issue Face Punishment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305020794 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 3 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305020794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Two quarantine officials will face punishment for 
their alleged roles in allowing importers to market frozen 
U.S.-made frankfurters here despite their original labels 
instructing "keep refrigerated." 
  An inspection team at the Ministry of Health and Social 
Affairs detected illegal practices by 24 importers in March and 
the ministry ordered them to destroy frankfurters valued at 19 
billion won, although two-thirds had already been sold. 
  The officials are Chang Chun-sik, 48, who now works for the 
National Institute for Safety Research, and Chi Yong-ae, 37, at 
the Pusan National Quarantine Station (PNQS). 
  The ministry yesterday asked a disciplinary committee of the 
Government Administration Ministry to determine their 
punishment. Chang and Chi, who worked together for the PNQS in 
November 1990, permitted importers to extend expiration dates of 
refrigerated sausages from 30 days to 90 days as if they had 
been frozen. 

</TEXT>

