<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officials on Businessman's Retirement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Officials on Businessman's Retirement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0305093494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0819 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0305093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 3 (YONHAP) -- Senior government and 
ruling Democratic Liberal Party (DLP) officials are far from 
impressed by Chong Chu-yong's announced intention to stay away 
from management of the Hyundai Business Group, it was learned 
Tuesday. 
  Chong announced his retirement from his group's management 
Tuesday morning at a press conference held shortly before his 
departure to Japan. 
  But since he said he would stay on as Hyundai's honorary 
chairman and provide advice to the group if necessary, officials 
at Chongwadae [presidential office], the presidential mansion, 
and the DLP do not think Chong will actually withdraw from the 
group's management. 
  A Chongwadae official, citing these reasons, called Chong's 
press conference "of no avail." 
  In spite of Chong's proclaimed retirement, the strained 
relations between the government and Hyundai caused by his quest 
for the presidency and his allegedly illegal means of financing 
his election campaign are expected to continue, according to the 
officials. 
  Since the presidential election in December 1992, Hyundai 
has 
received no financial support for facility investment from the 
Korea Development Bank and has not been allowed to open 
subsidiaries or to register in the over-the-counter market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

