<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farm Market Brokers Continue Strike Against Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farm Market Brokers Continue Strike Against Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0405095694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0812 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0405095694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 4 (YONHAP) -- Farm market brokers 
continued to strike against the new law on farm produce 
distribution and price stabilization for the second straight day 
Wednesday, paralyzing major agricultural markets across the 
country. 
  The new law prevents them from engaging in retail and 
wholesale business, among other things, causing an outpouring of 
anger. 
  In a meeting held Wednesday, the brokers resolved to 
continue 
their "work-to-rule struggle" until the government amends the 
law. 
  The government, meanwhile, flatly rejected their demand 
Wednesday by deciding not to revise the law. A senior 
presidential aide said, "there is no such thing as the principle 
of the law, which has been pushed for in the perspective of 
reform, to be retracted or re- amended. The brokers' act can by 
no means be accepted from the viewpoint of either the producers 
or consumers." 
  He said, "the government should, on the contrary, see to it 
that this incident be used as an opportunity for a structural 
reform of distribution of farm and fishery products to be 
facilitated." 
  Earlier in the day, Prime Minister Yi Yong-tok instructed 
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Choe In-ki to 
relieve the farm market paralysis created by the brokers' strike. 
  Should the brokers continue to strike, the government will 
accuse them of "group egoism" and take punitive steps including 
investigation of their account books for heavy taxation, 
officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

