<DOCNO> FBIS4-51924 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas086_d_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-086 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Security Council Action `Inevitable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Security Council Action `Inevitable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0405054394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0531 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0405054394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 4 (YONHAP) -- If North Korea continues to 
reject additional inspections of its nuclear sites, further 
action by the United Nations Security Council is inevitable, Yi 
Hong-ku, deputy prime minister and minister of the National 
Unification Board, said Wednesday. 
  Yi gave a briefing on the "recent North Korean situation and 
inter-Korean relations" at a meeting of the Advisory Council on 
Democratic and Peaceful Unification, saying that Pyongyang will 
eventually change its attitude because it has no good reason to 
delay settlement of the nuclear problem. 
  The newly appointed minister said, "Respecting the principle 
that the unification policy should maintain coherence, the 
government will adjust its direction according to changes in the 
situation as well as continue to study detailed ways to push 
ahead with this policy." 
  He said the Seoul government will deal separately with the 
nuclear and humanitarian issues. 
  "The government's decision to bring in North Koreans who 
escaped from the Siberian logging camps was made from a 
humanitarian point of view," Yi pointed out. 
  He clarified that the government will emphasize its 
unification policy in settling the North Korean dispute. 
  "Unless the deadlock on the nuclear issue is broken, the 
government will stick to its policy of linking the North Korean 
nuclear problem to inter-Korean economic cooperation," he said. 
  Seoul will continue to maintain the principles of 
inter-Korean relations -- settlement between the countries 
concerned, settlement between the governments, productive 
dialogue and implementation of agreements -- in pushing ahead 
with South-North dialogue, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

