Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Faces `Self-Destruction' on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    North Faces `Self-Destruction' on Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0405110694 Seoul YONHAP in English 1057 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0405110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 4 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam on 
Wednesday warned that if North Korea persists in going nuclear 
and tries to test the West's patience, they would have no 
alternative but to face self-destruction. 
  Saying that North Korea is trying to develop nuclear arms 
with an aim not at Japan, China or Russia but at South Korea, 
Kim said, "Our patience has come to a limit. North Korean 
nuclear development should be thwarted by all means." 
  President Kim made the remarks at a tea party he hosted at 
Chongwadae [presidential offices] for about 500 steering and 
standing committee members of the Advisory Council for 
Democratic and Peaceful Unification. 
  "I hope North Korean authorities will realize that their 
acceptance of nuclear inspection and return to genuine dialogue 
for peace will be the only way for the survival of themselves 
and the Korean nation," Kim said. 
  He said he is willing to talk openheartedly with North 
Korean 
authorities on pending inter-Korean issues including the nuclear 
question if they unconditionally accept international inspection 
of their nuclear facilities. 
  The Chongwadae reception was also attended by Deputy Prime 
Minister and National Unification Minister Yi Hong-ku. Among 
the attending advisory council leaders were council Vice 
Chairman Kim Myong-yun and Council Secretary General Yu 
Kyong-hyon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

