<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dialogue With DPRK Supported Over Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dialogue With DPRK Supported Over Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405134494 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 May 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0405134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A MAINICHI SHIMBUN opinion poll shows nearly 70 
percent of the respondents want the issue of North Korea's 
suspected nuclear arms program to be resolved by dialogue and 
not by sanctions. As regards Japan's participation in the UN 
Security Council as a permanent member, while 45 percent of the 
respondents said they "support" it, 43 percent said they "don't 
have an answer." This indicates that the public does not yet 
have a full understanding of the issue. 
  MAINICHI SHIMBUN conducted a nationwide survey by 
interviewing 3,000 eligible voters on 22-24 April, with 76 
percent responding. 
  Regarding North Korea's nuclear arms development program, 26 
percent said they are "greatly concerned," and 43 percent said 
they are "somewhat concerned." Thus a total of 69 percent of 
the respondents were found to be concerned about the issue. On 
the other hand, the proportion of respondents who said they were 
"not much concerned" amounted to 20 percent, and those who said 
they are "not concerned at all" totaled 10 percent. 
  When asked about ways to resolve this issue, 71 percent 
said: 
"Concerned nations should continue dialogue with North Korea to 
persuade it to accept inspections by the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA)." This number substantially exceeded the 
13 percent of respondents who said: "Economic sanctions must be 
taken against North Korea." Only 4 percent said: "There is no 
need to ask North Korea to accept inspections." Broken down by 
the political parties supported by the respondents, 17 percent 
of the Liberal Democratic Party supporters and 16 percent of 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] supporters replied "economic 
sanctions must be taken," while high rates of 85 percent of 
Japan New Party supporters and 82 percent of Sakigake 
[Harbinger] supporters replied "it should be resolved through 
dialogue." 
  Compared with when the last poll was conducted in September 
1993, the proportion of respondents who "supported" Japan's 
participation in the UN Security Council as a permanent member 
decreased by 2 points to 45 percent. The number of those who 
"opposed" it also decreased by 1 point to 10 percent. 
  However, the number of respondents who said they "don't have 
an answer" regarding Japan's participation totalled 43 percent, 
an increase of 5 points over the last poll. Among male 
respondents, 55 percent said they "supported" it, 11 percent 
said they "opposed" it, and 31 percent said they "don't have an 
answer." Of female respondents, 36 percent said they 
"supported" it, 9 percent "opposed" it, and 53 percent said they 
"don't have an answer." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51930 </DOCNO>
