<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Watanabe Views New Cabinet, Outlook for LDP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Watanabe Views New Cabinet, Outlook for LDP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0505023694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 April 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0505023694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Summary" of interview with Former Deputy Prime Minister </F>
Michio Watanabe of the LDP by YOMIURI SHIMBUN on 28 April; place 
not given] 
  [Text] [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Could you give your comments on 
the newly formed cabinet of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata? 
  [Watanabe] I thought the coalition might leave some cabinet 
posts open and headhunt senior members of the Liberal Democratic 
Party [LDP] and the Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] to 
fill vacancies in six cabinet posts (which were occupied by the 
SDPJ under the Hosokawa administration). So I am glad to see 
they filled the cabinet posts at once. I think the cabinet 
lineup is satisfactory, considering the people the coalition had 
available. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] What is your opinion on calls for 
dissolution of the lower house or the mass resignation of the 
cabinet immediately after enactment of the fiscal 1995 budget? 
  [Watanabe] At the end of the ongoing session, the Diet will 
have to discuss scandals (involving former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa) and other pending issues, and a no-confidence 
motion may be brought forward depending on manners (of the Hata 
administration). If the SDPJ supports the motion, the Hata 
cabinet would have to decide whether to resign en masse or 
dissolve the lower house. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] If the Hata cabinet is forced to resign, 
do you think it is possible to form a coalition government made 
up of the LDP and SDPJ? 
  [Watanabe] If the two parties form a coalition without a 
clear policy accord, the administration will meet the same fate 
as the Hosokawa administration. It would be difficult (to form 
a full-fledged administration of the two parties). The 
resignation of the Hata cabinet is more likely to result in a 
realignment of political parties. The SDPJ should take a more 
realistic attitude toward security ties with the United States. 
With respect to legislation for emergency situations (in 
connection with the Korean peninsula), Japan cannot be freed 
from logistics support duties. (In the case of an emergency), 
the Self-Defense Forces are supposed to supply fuel and 
provisions to U.S. vessels in operation. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Some quarters say confusion in political 
circles should be cleared up by an immediate general election. 
Do you agree? 
  [Watanabe] I think that is the due process of constitutional 
politics. It would not hurt the political reform laws. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Could you describe the LDP's strategy for 
winning back ruling power? 
  [Watanabe] I believe the LDP must try harder to change its 
negative image, as its policies are widely supported by the 
public. Of course, the LDP's drastic renovation may include a 
change of the party's name. The question here is whether or not 
we are ready to take action. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] LDP President Yohei Kono is critical of 
the political manners of Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro 
Ozawa. What is your comment on that point? 
  [Watanabe] So many people think so, and I was surprised when 
I noticed how many people dislike him. I did not realize it at 
all. They say he is too opinionated and secretive. In fact, the 
people are afraid of his dictatorship under the single-seat 
constituency system. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] But, Mr. Watanabe, you are still looking 
for a policy-oriented merger of conservative parties, are you 
not? 
  [Watanabe] I have been saying it is more natural to join 
forces with those who have common goals and methodology. I 
wonder why everybody does not do that. Politics must not be run 
on grudges. Based on emotions, people are saying they hate the 
LDP and some other parties. He (Ozawa) also has some points 
which merit blame; he should correct his manners a little. I 
think he is a man of deed who has clear ideas. 
  [YOMIURI SHIMBUN] Can you and President Kono win back the 
LDP's ruling position? 
  [Watanabe] I am not sure about that until I actually face 
the situation. At the least, I will try. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

