<H3> <TI>   `Ridiculous', `Imprudent' Act Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Ridiculous', `Imprudent' Act Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0505051994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0503 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0505051994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Ridiculous and Imprudent Act" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, May 5 (KCNA) -- The South Korean 
authorities decided to hold a meeting of the "Unification and 
Security Policy Coordinating Council" on May 6 in order to 
confirm their position that the replacement of the Armistice 
Agreement with a peace agreement which the North proposed to the 
United States must be discussed through direct North-South 
dialogue after the complete settlement of the nuclear issue of 
the North and notify the United States and the United Nations of 
this position. 
  Papers here today brand this as a ridiculous and imprudent 
act. 
  An analyst of NODONG SINMUN says: 
  The replacement of the Korean Armistice Agreement with a 
peace agreement and establishment of a new peace arrangement are 
questions that can be solved only between the DPRK and the 
United States, the parties concerned for the Armistice 
Agreement. The authorities of South Korea, not a signatory to 
the Armistice Agreement, are not qualified or justified for 
poking their nose in it. 
  It is the United States that holds all powers in South Korea 
including the military prerogative. Therefore, the question of 
the replacement of the Armistice Agreement with a peace 
agreement cannot be solved through dialogue with the South 
Korean authorities who are deprived of the military prerogative. 
  The South Korean puppets' opposition to DPRK-USA negotiation 
for peace on the pretext of the "settlement of the nuclear issue 
of the North" and their call for "direct North-South dialogue" 
clearly show that they want neither the settlement of the 
nuclear issue nor the establishment of new peace arrangement. 
  Their ulterior intention is to block the DPRK-USA 
negotiation 
for peace arrangement at any cost. 
  If the South Korean authorities want peace, they must not 
obstruct the DPRK-USA negotiation for the establishment of a new 
peace arrangement. 
  An analyst of MINJU CHOSON warns that if the South Korean 
puppets continue to resort to despicable acts to prevent the 
realisation of the just proposal of the North, they will 
encounter bitterer criticism and rejection from the people at 
home and abroad. 

</TEXT>

