<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farmers Begin Transplanting Maize Seedlings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farmers Begin Transplanting Maize Seedlings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2704042594 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0418 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2704042594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 27 (KCNA) -- The transplanting of 
humus-potted maize seedlings began in the Korean countryside. 
  Co-op farmers across the country have grown sturdy maize 
seedlings for reaping a bumper maize harvest again this year. 
  They do farming on a scientific and technical basis on the 
principle of the right crop in the right time and the right crop 
on the right soil. This year, too, they began transplanting 
humus-potted maize seedlings all at once as the right time came. 
  Rural communities now are overfulfilling daily quotas by use 
of various highly-efficient machines including tractors and 
fertilizer-spraying machines. 
  The transplanting of humus-potted maize seedlings is one of 
the important farming processes in Korea. 

</TEXT>

