<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farm Brokers End Strike After Farm Law Shelved </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farm Brokers End Strike After Farm Law Shelved </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0405111294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1059 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0405111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 4 (YONHAP) -- Farm and fishery market 
brokers ended their two-day strike Wednesday evening after the 
government decided [to] shelve the planned enforcement of the 
new law on farm produce distribution and price stabilization for 
the next six months. 
  Yi Chong-su, secretary of the Association of Brokers Unions, 
said his association members would return to normal farm and 
fishery goods wholesaling and auctioning on Wednesday evening. 
  "I think the Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry, 
which had taken a mistaken policy, seems to have come to know 
the sufferings of farm and fishery goods producers," Yi said. 
  Market brokers went on a strike on Tuesday in protest 
against 
the implementation of the new law which they argued would 
heavily undermine their interests. 

