<H3> <TI>   Farm Minister Changes in Food Control System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farm Minister Changes in Food Control System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405015394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0405015394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Mutsuki Kato, minister of agriculture, </F>
forestry, and fisheries, by unidentified NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 
correspondent; place and date not given; from the "Interview 
With Hata Cabinet Members in Charge of Economic Matters" series; 
one of two interviews comprising second part of series: "Public 
Debate on Rice Prices"] 
  [Text] [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Following the recent uproar 
over rice, the people have intensified their criticism of the 
current food control system. 
  [Kato] But I think the food control system helped settle the 
confusion at an early date. It seems the concept of staple food 
is not common in the United States and European countries. I 
think it is Japan's characteristic concept. The recent uproar 
was the event which made us reaffirm the importance of a stable 
supply of rice. Because rice is storable, I would like to 
promote arguments about storing rice from now on. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] When you were farm minister in 1986, 
you asserted that the essence of the food control system be 
maintained. 
  [Kato] I would like to back down a little from that position 
and say the basis of the food control system should be 
maintained. Japan has accepted minimum access of rice (minimum 
import quota); as such, we do not say no to everything. I will 
think things over by taking a different position from that which 
I took before. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Do you mean you will promote reform 
of the food control system? 
  [Kato] I would like to promote agricultural administration 
in such a way that it benefits the people. On the other hand, I 
have to consider two issues, which are, ensuring a stable food 
supply and heightening farmers' will to farm. We are now in 
difficult times, far more difficult than when I was farm 
minister before. Also, because the Hata cabinet is a minority 
government, it is certain to have tough times. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] What is your opinion about rice 
prices? 
  [Kato] The government-purchased rice is priced at 300,000 
yen per ton, while Thai-grown rice is sold at about 40,000 to 
60,000 yen in Thailand. Because the people now eat 
foreign-grown rice, they know about this. The government needs 
to discuss rice prices with the people, while taking into 
consideration rice growers and agricultural organizations. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Do you not think the imported rice 
sold in Japan is high priced? 
  [Kato] Certainly, it is priced a little high. But because 
the government imported rice as an emergency measure to fill the 
shortage of rice caused by a poor crop at home, high prices are 
inevitable. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Is it possible to reduce the price of 
rice, which is to be imported next year and beyond, in 
accordance with the minimum access agreement? 
  [Kato] This is a difficult issue. We will have in-depth 
discussions on this issue. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] There are many farmers who sell their 
rice on the black market, where rice is traded at high prices. 
  [Kato] They should think about how long the current high 
prices will be maintained. In the near future, the rice crop 
will be average. I hope farmers will realize this. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] The Hata cabinet backed by a minority 
ruling coalition will have to have the Uruguay Round agreement 
ratified by the Diet this autumn. 
  [Kato] We intend to have the agreement ratified by all 
means. This issue concerns Japan's role in the international 
community. Diet members will be asked to act sensibly, and not 
be bound by their positions as ruling and opposition parties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-52029 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas088__a94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-088-A </AU>
